node.text: One of my favorite interviews on Your Faves Faves just came out and if you love country music (or honestly, any kind of music) please come nerd out with me while I ask my buddy @bradpaisley 1,000 questions about how he writes, sings, dreams up music, plans a duet and what all those guitars are for. The link is in my bio!

node.title: Brad Paisley and I Talk Country Music

node.text: I had an idea for my podcast. I wanted to talk about the Law of Attraction + Manifesting and the difference between the two. It was a spur of the moment thing and so I knocked it out quickly on my phone and sent it to my producer not totally sure if listeners would be interested in the topic. Um, y’all were IN. Last week’s episode (Ep. 185) is, apparently, as interesting to you as it is to me. I’ve already gotten SO many follow up questions and I promise I’ll do a deeper dive. In the meantime though, if you want to listen in to how your focus, intention, thoughts are creating the life you have today and how it affects your ability to achieve your goals the link is in my bio. 🤟🏻

node.text:
Today on the Rachel Hollis Podcast I’m diving into EVERYTHING that has helped me manage my anxiety over the last decade. Therapy, adaptogens, movement, nutrition, meditation, journaling... I’ve tested it all and I hope hearing about my journey will help you get ideas for your own.

I also dive down a little bit of a rabbit hole on anxiety related to people pleasing which SO many women I know struggle with, especially if you’re a high achiever. Enneagram 3’s I see you!!

You can listen in through the link in my bio or wherever you get your podcasts. 🤟🏻

node.text:
I am so excited to welcome my dear friend @amyporterfield to our podcast network!!

Why is it that a woman can be successful on EVERY level and still feel like a failure because they’re not at the “right” weight? Why is it that women feel like success has ANYTHING to do with their appearance?? Amy and I started this conversation on a girl’a trip back in 2019... we continued it on the RISE stage in 2020 and the response from our community was so overwhelming we’ve expanded it into a podcast. This is an incredibly vulnerable topic and I couldn’t be prouder of Amy for taking it on. Here’s what the new show is about 👇🏻

| Amy Porterfield has experienced massive success in both her business and personal life, but behind every accomplishment lingered a nagging suspicion that she wasn’t living up to some invisible standard of how she should look. Now she’s on a mission to discover exactly where that little voice inside her head came from, and - together with some new friends and fresh perspectives - how she can vanquish it once and for all. 

Listen in to my interview with Amy on today’s podcast and then go check out Talking Body wherever you get your podcasts.

node.title: Our NEW Podcast: Talking Body w/ Amy Porterfield

node.text:
When I saw that @ericclapton was coming to Austin I knew I had to go.

Why? Well, it’s Eric Clapton and he’s so damn good it almost hurts your feelings to watch him play -- literally top 3 greatest concerts of my life and if you ever get the chance to go see him, please take it! But also, because he was my brother’s favorite artist and after Ryan died, his music became especially poignant for me. To this day, whenever I hear Tears in Heaven I always receive it as a message of love from my big brother. 

20 years ago I took my dad to see Clapton in LA --it was a really emotional night for us because we were only 4 years removed from his death and we both felt Ryan’s absence keenly. As it happened, we got to Staples Center late (LA Traffic is real!) and the lights were already down-- an usher had to walk us to our seats with a flashlight. A couple of minutes later, the lights came up as Eric walked on stage and it was the first time I noticed, in a sold out, fully-packed arena, there was one empty seat… right next to me. I tapped my dad on the shoulder and pointed it out to him and both our eyes filled with tears. Ryan was with us that night, he had his own seat and everything. 

Last night, I attended the concert alone-- I didn’t know any Clapton fans to bring along and I figured, I’m grown up enough to go to a show by myself... and somehow, I knew that I wouldn’t be. When I got to my seat, I wasn’t surprised at all to discover the chair next to mine was empty… in a packed house of thousands. It still brings tears to my eyes to think about it now. 

If you’ve lost someone, I hope telling you this story might encourage you to open your heart to the messages that are all around you. The loved-ones we’ve lost are never truly gone and there’s comfort in connecting to them or their memory in a way that feels good to you. 

September (the month my brother took his own life) is also National Suicide Prevention month. To find out more information, two of my favorite organizations to learn from and donate to are @namicommunicate + @trevorproject 🤟🏻 #suicidepreventionmonth

node.text:
“Please don’t quit. Please, please don’t stop showing up.”

This letter was beautiful and kind and so I just wanted to take a quick moment to say: hi.

And also, I’m not quitting. Y’all know me... I’ll keep showing up even when I’m stumbling and getting it wrong... that forward momentum is the only way I can learn and do better. I’m not quitting, but I am moving at a much slower pace so I can learn what I’m meant to be learning. I’m not present here on social because the work I’m doing isn’t external— it’s for my heart and my friends and my community and so I can be proud of myself as a woman and as an example for my children.

At some point, I’ll be back with awkward stories and too much coffee, and a better perspective on what it is to love well. But until then, I’m moving slowly. And for my sweet friend who sent the letter, thank you for caring enough to send a note of encouragement to a stranger...it means more to me than you will ever know. xo, Rach
